{[%evp 0,105,14,28,28,28,27,29,49,40,39,39,32,17,33,30,20,12,3,10,-5,8,39,33,
50,46,73,58,51,46,38,41,49,24,33,30,24,31,32,39,65,57,48,46,45,35,46,44,75,59,
69,59,53,41,43,45,44,52,54,40,77,85,86,74,73,74,103,83,125,86,105,108,106,105,
105,91,127,123,110,116,123,108,116,120,132,129,151,148,190,207,189,180,309,309,
307,263,299,299,289,444,447,458,458,386,386,390,399,399] Even though this game
features the London System, it's a very good illustration of the drawbacks
behind the concepts based on ...cxd4 in connection with ...d7-d5. White's
approach in this game is very similar to the play of Spassky from the previous
example.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 Be7 6. h3 c5 7. O-O
O-O 8. Nbd2 Nc6 {For the time being, Black prefers to keep the d-pawn flexible.
Nevertheless, sooner or later, he will have to play ...d7-d5, thus entering
the type of position we are familiar with.} 9. c3 d5 10. Qe2 cxd4 $2 {As we
know from the previous example, this is a huge positional mistake. In the
arising positions, Black does not have any counterplay.} ({Another serious
concession would be the advance} 10... c4 $2 {when after} 11. Bc2 b5 {White
has a free hand on the kingside since there is no central tension. In my
opinion, the most straightforward continuation is} 12. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5]
planning e4-e5 with a fantastic French structure. Note that White should play
a2-a3 when Black needs to spend a few tempis on preparing ...b5-b4. This is
not the case here, since a2-a3 would be met by the immediate ...a7-a5.} ({
Another option is} 12. Ne5 {with the idea to gradually build a kingside attack.
})) 11. exd4 $16 {Black is left without a plan! Additionally the b7-bishop is
just terrible!} Nd7 {This is a logical move. Black tries to increase his
control of the e5-square.} ({It is very important to remember that the
minority attack does not work when the light-squared bishop is stuck behind
the pawn chain. The following variation is quite a good example -} 11... a6 12.
Rfe1 ({Another attacking approach is} 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 b5 14. a3 {It
turns out that Black's minority attack has practically stopped.} Rc8 15. Bxf6
Bxf6 16. f4 {with a huge advantage. White has all the time in the world to
organize his kingside attack.}) 12... b5 13. a3 ({A more radical option would
be} 13. b4 {This move works well when Black does not have ...e6-e5 at his
disposal.}) 13... Na5 {Even if Black puts his knight on c4, he does not have
queenside counterplay.} 14. Rad1 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] This is only one of all
the natural moves.} ({Another typical idea is} 14. Bg5 {with the idea to answer
} Nc4 {with} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3c5] making use of the c5-square.
After} Be7 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. dxc5 $16 {the c5-pawn, as well as the active minor
pieces, give White an obvious advantage.}) ({An alternative way of fighting
for the c5-square is} 14. b4 Nc4 15. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3c5]} Ne4 16. Qc2 Rc8 17. Nc5
{Black will be forced to exchange the annoying c5-knight, thus allowing White
to obtain a strong protected passed pawn.}) 14... Nc4 15. Nf1 Ne4 16. Ng3 {
After exchanging the e4-knight, White would enjoy a free hand on the kingside.}
) 12. Rfe1 Re8 13. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1h2,Gh2g4] The idea of this move is to
transfer the knight to g4 in order to fight for the e5-square.} Nf8 14. N1h2
Ng6 15. Bg3 Bd6 16. Ne5 $1 {In my opinion, this is the most ambitious approach.
} ({Another possibility would have been} 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. g3 $14 {[%cal Gh3h4,
Gh4h5,Gh2g4] White is again better. He can now proceed with h3-h4-h5 followed
by Ng4.}) 16... Ncxe5 17. dxe5 {As we know from the game Spassky - Matanovic,
this structural transformation is favourable for White.} Bc5 18. Nf3 {[%cal
Gh3h4] White is ready to expand with the thematic h3-h4-h5.} a5 {[%csl Gc5]
Trying to secure the position of the c5-bishop.} ({The thematic reaction to} 
18... d4 {is} 19. c4 {[%csl Gd3] The d3-bishop is a monster now. Besides
blocking the d4-pawn, it also participates in the attack. Now, White is ready
to follow with h3-h4-h5.} ({There is nothing wrong with} 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. cxd4
Qxd4 21. Rad1 {with a strong initiative.})) 19. h4 Nf8 20. Rad1 $1 {White
anticipates Black's idea of exchanging the light-squared bishops.} Qc8 21. Qd2
$1 {The idea behind 20.Rad1 becomes clear now. White is ready to answer} Ba6 {
with} 22. Bb1 $1 {Black does not have any counterplay. Therefore, White has a
lot of time to gradually build his kingside attack.} Ra7 23. h5 Qd8 24. Nd4 Rc7
25. Qf4 {All white pieces slowly start occupying positions near the black king.
Black is forced to keep waiting passively. The next moves are quite logical.}
h6 26. Nf3 Be7 27. Qg4 Kh8 28. Nd4 Bc5 29. Re3 Nh7 30. Bh4 Be7 31. Bxe7 Qxe7
32. f4 {White enjoys a classical advantage that is very typical for the French
Defence.} Rg8 33. Rde1 Bc8 34. Rg3 Qc5 35. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Gb1d3] This move will
be followed by Bd3 in order to stop all Black's attempts to play ...b6-b5.} Bd7
36. Bd3 Qe7 37. Rf1 Qd8 38. a3 $1 {Similar to the prophylactic approach of
Boris Spassky. Since I am not in a hurry at all, I prefer to eliminate even
the slightest possible counterplay.} Qe7 39. Re3 Qd8 40. Qf2 Qe8 41. g4 {
Since it's impossible to further improve the position of the pieces, it's time
for an attack. White managed to easily convert his advantage into a full point.
} Qd8 42. Rg3 Bc8 43. Qe3 g6 44. hxg6 fxg6 45. Kg2 Nf8 46. Rh1 Rh7 47. Kf2 Kg7
48. f5 Qg5 49. f6+ Kf7 50. Qxg5 hxg5 51. Rxh7+ Nxh7 52. Rh3 Nxf6 (52... Nf8 53.
Nf3 Ke8 54. Nxg5) 53. Rf3 1-0

