{[%evp 0,77,18,17,17,17,17,24,21,8,41,19,8,8,8,0,11,13,26,32,44,44,51,41,63,63,
71,69,58,70,69,64,68,76,76,76,76,65,81,81,82,79,100,86,108,100,103,100,94,92,
92,72,75,99,106,108,102,114,127,58,33,90,144,141,156,81,247,194,200,200,200,
228,232,232,232,15,400,523,29991,29992] IN VERY SIMILAR STYLE WITH THE GAME
Papaioannou-Mastrovasilis A. (with the typical mistake cd4? ..in connection
with the move d5 by black !!!)} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 d5 5. Nbd2
Nc6 6. c3 h6 7. Bh4 ({Another decent option is the transposition into the
London System with} 7. Bf4 {In this case, Black's extra tempo ...h7-h6 is
favourable only for White. The reason is that White can use the h6-pawn as a
hook which makes White's kingside attack a lot faster.}) 7... cxd4 $2 {As I
have pointed out in the introduction to this lecture, after playing ...d7-d5,
Black should never take on d4. The reason is that White increases his control
of the important squares e3, e4, and e5. Usually, in such kinds of positions,
Black does not have any counterplay.} 8. exd4 Be7 9. Bd3 Nh5 {Exchanging
White's dark-squared bishop does not allow Black to solve his opening problems.
} 10. Bxe7 {This is the classical reaction to ...Nh5.} ({Nevertheless, I would
even prefer} 10. Bg3 {when after} Nxg3 11. hxg3 O-O 12. O-O {Black's bishop
pair is not significant at all. Besides his firm control of the e-file, White
enjoys additional attacking possibilities on the kingside. In this regard, a
very typical idea would be g2-g3 followed by Kg2, and Rh1. In such a case,
Black should always reckon with the advance g4-g5.}) 10... Qxe7 11. O-O Nf4 12.
Bc2 {Of course, we should preserve our light-squared bishop.} Qf6 13. Re1 O-O
14. g3 $1 {Pay attention to this very important move. By kicking the knight
back, White prepares the move 15.Qe2. In this way, he connects the rooks and
increases the control of the strategically important e5-square.} Ng6 15. Qe2 $1
{Black does not have any counterplay in this position since the advances ...
e6-e5 as well as ...b7-b5 are not possible. At the same time, White is ready
to develop his kingside activity. As always, the most thematic idea is Ne5.
With the black knight being on g6, the advance ...h2-h4-h5 is getting even
more tempting. In the future, Black also might face problems on the diagonal
b1-h7. One can easily see the tremendous difference in the activity of the
light-squared bishops.} b6 16. h4 Re8 17. Ne5 $1 {Whenever Black threatens ...
e6-e5, we should play this move.} Ncxe5 18. dxe5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd2f3,Gf3d4]
This transformation of the pawn structure is usually very favourable for White.
The e5-pawn seizes a lot of space and provides White with tremendous attacking
potential. Additionally, the d4-square is now vacant for the knight.} Qe7 19.
Nf3 a5 20. Nd4 $1 {White's position is strategically winning. The way in which
Spassky converts his advantage is very instructive.} ({You shouldn't be
tempted by} 20. Bxg6 $6 {when after} fxg6 21. Nd4 Ba6 22. Qe3 Rf8 {Black's
position is still holdable.}) 20... Bd7 21. Bd3 $1 {Directed against ...b6-b5.
Having a stable advantage, White does not give the slightest counterplay to
his opponent.} Rab8 22. a4 $1 {I like this move a lot. Even though White could
have focused on his kingside play, the prophylactic thinking of Spassky is
amazing.} Nf8 23. f4 Rec8 24. Kh2 {Since Black does not have any counterplay,
White can slowly prepare for his attack.} Qe8 25. g4 $1 {Finally! The a4-pawn
is not important at all. White has a powerful kingside attack.} Ng6 ({After} 
25... Bxa4 {both} 26. g5 ({and} 26. f5 {are possible.})) 26. Qf2 Qe7 27. h5 $1
Nf8 ({Exchanging the queens with} 27... Qh4+ {does not help Black. After} 28.
Qxh4 Nxh4 29. Kg3 g5 30. hxg6 Nxg6 31. f5 $18 {White's attack is crushing even
without queens.}) 28. Rg1 {[%cal Gg4g5] White is preparing the advance g4-g5.}
f6 (28... Rc7 29. g5 hxg5 30. Rxg5 $18) 29. Rae1 Bxa4 30. Qg3 Be8 31. exf6 Qxf6
({After} 31... gxf6 32. Nf5 Qc7 33. g5 $18 {Black is going to be mated.}) 32.
Re5 Qf7 33. g5 $3 {White is winning. Matanovic resigned in a few moves.} Qxh5+
34. Kg2 hxg5 35. fxg5 Qf7 36. Rf1 Qe7 37. g6 Rc4 38. Rh5 Rxd4 39. Rxf8+ 1-0

