{This game is very typical for the so-called Pilsbury Attack. Even though
White finally lost, he played brilliantly and got a huge advantage.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Nbd2 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 b6 8. Ne5 $1 {
In my opinion, this is the most precise move order. In order to justify this
jump, however, White should choose the optimal follow-up.} ({As we will see in
the next examples, another possible idea in such positions is} 8. h4) ({Even} 
8. O-O {is possible. Note that exchanging the light-squared bishops with} Ba6
9. Bxa6 Nxa6 {does not manage to solve Black's problems. Black will need to
invest some time to reroute the a6-knight. Meanwhile, White will organize
kingside activity. For example, after} 10. Ne5 Nb8 11. f4 Qc7 12. Qf3 Nc6 13.
g4 {White has still attacking potential on the kingside.}) 8... Bb7 {The most
natural continuation.} ({With the white knight being on e5, the move} 8... Ba6
{is not that effective in view of} 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Nc6 Qd7 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12.
O-O $14 {White is still better but this time he is not going to play for a
kingside attack. A nice way to transform the structure is dxc5 followed by
e3-e4.} ({It's also possible to start with} 12. Qe2) 12... Nb8 {Black usually
plays this move.} ({After} 12... cxd4 13. exd4 {White gets his dream pawn
structure. I remind you that ...cxd4 is never a good move in connection with ..
.d7-d5.}) ({The generally desirable} 12... e5 $2 {does not work due to
tactical reasons -} 13. dxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf3 Qe6 15. Bxf6 {Due to the vulnerable
d5-pawn, Black should recapture with the pawn.} gxf6 (15... Qxf6 16. Qxd5 $18)
16. Ne1 (16. Nh4 $16) 16... Nc7 17. Nd3 $16 {[%cal Gd3f4] with Nf4 to follow.
White has an obvious advantage.}) 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. e4 $16 {White is slightly
better. Besides the annoying pin on the diagonal h4-d8, Black should take care
of his shaky pawn centre.}) 9. Bxf6 $3 {A very important move that always
comes into consideration when Black cannot recapture with a knight. Finally,
White does not need to reckon with the jump ...Ne4.} ({A very typical mistake
would be} 9. f4 $2 {when Black will immediately play} Ne4 $14 {, solving all
the problems. Once Black manages to play ...Ne4, White does not have an attack.
Additionally, ...f7-f6 is already on the agenda.}) ({Very nice but a bit more
sophisticated idea is} 9. h4 $1 Nbd7 {Black is planning to solve the problems
by means of ...Nxe5 followed by ...Ne4.} ({Inferior is} 9... Nc6 $6 10. f4 $16
{when Black does not have any counterplay since the ideas based on ...Ne4
never work.} ({Even more straightforward would be} 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6
12. f4 $16 {without knights, Black does not have active possibilities.
Meanwhile, White will keep developing his kingside play.}) 10... Nd7 11. Qh5 f5
12. g4 $16 {In this structure, the move ...f7-f5 is always well met by this
move. The kingside attack is very strong. A possible line would be} Ncxe5 13.
fxe5 g6 14. Qh6 Rf7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. O-O-O $18 {with a crushing attack.}) ({
I have also checked} 9... Ne4 {Since, the g5-bishop is now protected, White
can play} 10. Qg4 f5 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Qf4 $16 {with a big advantage. Besides
his control of the important e5-square, in a long run, White can prepare the
break g2-g4.}) 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 ({In case of} 10... Nxd7 {the best reaction is}
11. Qh5 {Usually, when the black knight leaves the f6-square, our queen comes
immediately.} g6 12. Qh6 $16 Re8 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. f4 {After having stopped
the advance ...e6-e5, White is preparing h4-h5. The endgame, arising after} Qf8
15. Qxf8+ (15. Qg5 $16) 15... Kxf8 {is clearly better for White. In my opinion,
he should start with} 16. Bb5 {with the idea to exchange Black's only active
piece.} Re7 17. Bxd7 Rxd7 18. h5 $16 cxd4 19. exd4 $16 {White has a
strategically winning position. After putting the knight on e5, he can double
the rooks on the h-file. Of course, seizing even more space on the kingside by
advancing the g-pawn is another major idea. Meanwhile, Black does not have any
counterplay at all.}) 11. Bxf6 $3 {Once again, we see this typical motif.
Before playing f2-f4, we make sure that Black does not have ...Ne4.} Bxf6 12.
f4 $16 {This is our favourite position. Black does not have any counterplay.
Before pushing the kingside paws, White can play Qh5 in order to provoke some
weakening pawn moves. For example, a black pawn on h6 or g6 would tremendously
speed up White's attack.}) ({Another typical way to play the position is} 9.
Qf3 $14 {Besides taking the e4-square under control, White is planning to
transfer the queen to h3.} Nc6 ({After} 9... Nbd7 {White can play} 10. Qh3 {
since} Ne4 {is well met by} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. f3 Nef6 (12... Ng5 13. Qg3) 13.
O-O {with decent attacking chances.}) 10. Bf4 {This position can also arise
via the London System. White is going to follow with either Qh3 or g2-g4. It's
not clear how Black will create counterplay.}) 9... Bxf6 10. f4 $14 {[%cal
Gd1h5] After depriving Black of the idea ...Ne4, White can start his kingside
operations.} Nd7 11. Nxd7 $1 {Of course! Without knights, Black does not have
counterplay.} ({The move} 11. Ndf3 {is possible as well. It's important,
however, to answer} Be7 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gf6e4] with} 12. Nxd7 {otherwise, Black
would have executed the maneuver ...Nf6-e4.}) 11... Qxd7 12. h4 $16 {Since the
centre is stable, White does not need to hurry up with castling.} (12. Nf3 $16
g6 13. h4) 12... cxd4 13. exd4 $16 {Whenever possible, we take with the e-pawn.
As usual, ...cxd4 is not well combined with ...d7-d5.} Qc7 14. Qh5 $1 {I like
this move very much. The idea is to provoke a kingside weakness.} ({Of course,
there is nothing wrong with} 14. g3 {Black does not have counterplay anyway.})
14... g6 15. Qf3 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h5 16. g4 {White's attack is already very
dangerous. Even though Caruana managed to win, it's clear that he didn't solve
his opening problems.} 0-1

