{This game features one of the most important types of position that a Torre
player must know. Black answers Ne5 with ...Nxe5, without previously
exchanging on d4. In this case, White accepts doubled pawns on the e-file.} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 h6 {Of course, Black can decide to play without ...
h7-h6. The character of the play would remain unchanged.} 4. Bh4 d5 5. e3 c5 6.
c3 {There is nothing particularly wrong with this move order.} ({Nevertheless,
my preference would be} 6. Nbd2 $1 {The most important idea behind the early
development of the knight is to answer ...Qb6 with Rb1. A possible line would
be} Nc6 7. c3 Qb6 8. Rb1 {At first sight, it might appear that our rook is
passive on b1. At the same time, however, Black's queen is also misplaced on
b6. While preparing our kingside attack, our task is to simply hold the
queenside without making any concessions.} Be7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Bd7 11. Ne5
Qd8 12. f4 {White got his dream position. Black does not have any counterplay
whatsoever.}) 6... Nc6 ({The move order starting with 6.c3 gives Black the
additional option of playing} 6... Qb6 {when White should play} 7. Qc1 {
The passivity of the queen, however, is not a permanent factor. White is still
better.} Nc6 8. Nbd2 Bd7 9. Rb1 $1 {Once again, this move is an important part
of White's strategy. White anticipates ...Rc8.} ({After} 9. Bd3 Rc8 10. Qb1 {
the White queen was forced into a passive square. The a1-rook is now stuck.})
9... Rc8 10. Qd1 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd1e2] White is heading for his normal type of
play. It's not clear how Black can benefit from the moves ...Qb6 and ...Rc8.}
Be7 ({Sometimes, Black can go for a Stonewall type of structure by means of} 
10... Ne4 11. Bd3 f5 {In this case, we shouldn't insist on our kingside attack.
The best strategy is to open the position by means of c3-c4. In this way,
White is going to make use of the weaknesses created by the advance ...f7-f5.}
12. O-O Bd6 13. c4 $1 cxd4 14. exd4 Nxd4 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Nxd4 {[%cal Gd1h5]
with Qh5 to follow. I am sure that Black would have loved to have his f-pawn
back on f7.}) 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O Rfd8 13. Ne5 Be8 14. f4 {We can play this
move since the black knight does not have access to the e4-square.} ({The
thematic} 14. Bxf6 $2 Bxf6 15. f4 {does not work tactically in view of the
opposition on the diagonal g1-a7.} cxd4 16. exd4 Bxe5 17. fxe5 Nxe5 $19 (17...
Nxd4 $19)) {If Black plays} 14... cxd4 {we are more than happy to answer with}
15. exd4 Qc7 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qe2 {when White obtains his typical advantage.})
7. Nbd2 Be7 ({As we are going to witness in the future examples, when Black
has a knight on c6, preparing ...e6-e5 with} 7... Bd6 {does not work
tactically -} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O e5 $6 ({After} 9... cxd4 10. exd4 e5 11. dxe5
Bxe5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 {the arising IQP position is always slightly more pleasant
for White.}) 10. e4 $3 $16 {This is the best move acording to the computer.} ({
Another solid way to the advantage is} 10. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. f4 $1
Bd6 13. e4 $1 {Black's position is already critical as proven by the following
lines.} dxe4 $2 (13... Be7 14. e5 (14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. e5 $16)) 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 $2
(14... gxf6 15. Nxe4) 15. Nxe4 Qe7 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Bh7+ $18) 10... cxd4 ({
After} 10... g5 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 $16 {White has more than enough
compensation for the piece. A possible line is} Be7 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. exd5 Qxd5
15. Qh5 Rd8 16. Bc4 $18 {with a winning attack.} Qd7 17. Ne4 Bg7 18. Ng5 $18
Qf5 19. f4 {Black can already resign.}) 11. exd5 Ne7 12. cxd4 exd4 13. Bxf6
gxf6 14. Bc4 $16 {With a tremendous advantage.}) 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O {The
precise move order.} ({Premature would be} 9. Ne5 $6 {in view of} Nd7 {when
simplifications favour Black.}) 9... b6 10. Ne5 $1 $14 {Now, this knight jump
works fine since Black does not have ...Nd7.} Nxe5 ({In case of} 10... Bb7 {
White has two good options -} 11. Nxc6 ({Of course, the alternative is} 11.
Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 12. f4 {when Black does not have counterplay at all.}) ({A
typical mistake will be} 11. f4 $2 {in view of} Ne4 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 {with an
acceptable position for Black. White does not have any kingside attack.}) 11...
Bxc6 12. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 13. f4 {[%cal Gd1h5] Black's position is very difficult.
The inclusion of the advance ...h7-h6 makes his position even worse. Now,
White has the idea of Qh5 followed by g2-g4-g5. In such cases, the h6-pawn is
the perfect hook that speeds up White's attack.}) 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Bxe7 {
This is the simplest way of handling the position.} ({Another possibility is} 
12. Bg3 $5 {I think, however, that this line is more complex and difficult to
handle.}) 12... Qxe7 13. f4 {The e5-pawn provides White with a considerable
space advantage. Therefore, White can start an attack by bringing his pieces
to the kingside. A typical move would be Qh5. Therefore, Black often tries to
fight for space by means of} f5 14. exf6 $1 {Regardless of whether Black plays
...f7-f6 or ...f7-f5, we should always take the pawn.} Nxf6 {This is the
optimal recapture.} ({The thematic reaction to} 14... Rxf6 {is} 15. e4 {
[%cal Ge4e5] planning to follow with e4-e5. If Black takes on e4, then his
pawn structure will be ruined. After} Bb7 16. e5 Rff8 17. Qg4 {White has a
very strong attack.}) ({After} 14... Qxf6 {, once again our best move is} 15.
e4 {with the same strategy. The next move is e4-e5.}) 15. Nf3 $1 {White
changes his strategy. This time, he will try to make use of the vulnerable
e5-square. When Black has a knight on f6, e3-e4 is not a good idea due to the
arising simplifications.} Nd7 16. Bb5 $1 {I like this move a lot. White has 2
ideas: 1) Bxd7 followed by Ne5, thus obtaining a classical advantage 2) Ba4-c2
followed by Qd3 which is very effective when Black has played ...h7-g6.} a6 17.
Ba4 $5 {This is a perfectly valid option. Having played ...a7-a6, Black does
not have ...Ba6 at his disposal.} ({The more classical way of handling the the
position would have been} 17. Bxd7 Bxd7 18. Ne5 $14 {White can play either on
the kingside and in the centre. Practice shows that the kingside attack is
more promising in such positions. Therefore, White will follow with simple
moves such as Qg4 and Rf3.}) 17... b5 18. Bc2 c4 {Stopping Qd3 at the price of
multiple weaknesses.} ({Nevertheless, even after} 18... Bb7 19. Qd3 Nf6 20. Ne5
{White is obviously better.}) 19. Qd2 Bb7 20. a4 {Opening a second battlefield.
White's advantage is beyond any doubt. Later on, he managed to convert it into
a full point.} e5 21. axb5 axb5 22. fxe5 Nxe5 23. Nxe5 Qxe5 24. Rxa8 Rxa8 25.
Qf2 Qe7 26. Qf5 g5 27. Qg6+ Qg7 28. Qe6+ 1-0

