{[%evp 0,45,31,14,28,28,28,12,12,14,7,9,11,14,11,14,20,-2,13,-24,-10,-28,16,21,
54,15,52,44,8,54,52,95,132,177,183,193,199,139,251,251,299,318,606,593,950,996,
897,986] Sometimes, after ...h7-h6, White can retreat his bishop to f4. In
this way, he gets a favourable version of the London System. Let's briefly
take a look at an example -} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 d5 4. e3 Be7 5. Nbd2
O-O 6. Bd3 h6 7. Bf4 $5 {With a black pawn on h7, we would have had a normal
London System. Actually, the advance ...h7-h6 is favourable for White since
the h6-pawn can be used as a hook for White's attack. This is what happened in
the game.} c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. Qe2 ({Another decent option would have been} 9. Ne5
$16 Qb6 10. Rb1 Qa5 11. a3 Bd7 12. g4 {with a strong attack for White.}) 9...
b6 10. g4 $16 {Matlakov immediately starts an attack. It turns out that Black
does not have enough counterplay. Later on, White managed to win rather
quickly.} cxd4 11. exd4 Ne8 12. Rg1 Bd6 13. Be3 f6 14. h4 e5 15. g5 e4 16. Nxe4
dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bd7 18. gxh6 Rf7 19. Qc4 Qe7 20. Bd5 Na5 21. Bxf7+ Kf8 22. h7
Nxc4 23. Bxc4 1-0

