[White "Setups with ...Qb6"]
[Black "General Ideas"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A46"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "19"]
[EventDate "2016.05.25"]
[EventType "swiss"]
[SourceVersionDate "2018.05.20"]

{Now, we shall take a look at the systems based on ...Qb6. Even though these
setups are ambitious and aggressive, it's White who will choose the pattern of
play. As it will become clear, he can play either positionally or dynamically.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 $5 4. e3 Qb6 $5 {This is the most precise move
order. If Black wants to opt for a setup based on ...Qb6, he should play this
move immediately. Now, White should decide what to do with the defence of the
b2-pawn.} ({The alternative move order} 4... cxd4 5. exd4 Qb6 {is inferior
since White can play} 6. Bc1 $3 $14 {This is probably the simplest move for a
small advantage! We lose a tempo but the queen on b6 is also misplaced!} ({
Of course, there is nothing wrong with} 6. Qc1 {when the game might follow with
} Nc6 7. c3 Ne4 8. Be3 d5 9. Nbd2 {From the previous examples, we know that
this position is statically favourable for White since ...cxd4 does not work
well in combination with ...d7-d5.} Bd7 $4 {This move loses by force but I
give it for illustration purposes.} ({Nothing changes} 9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 {
with a classical advantage for White.}) {This is a typical move in such
positions. The idea is to free the queen from the defence of the b2-pawn. In
this structure, we can afford to play passively on the queenside while
focusing our attacking attempts on the kingside.} 10. Rb1 ({Of course,} 10.
Nxe4 dxe4 11. d5 $18 {is winning by force.}) 10... Rc8 11. Qd1 {As always
happens in this pawn structure, White has a big advantage.}) 6... Nc6 7. c3 Be7
8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Qc7 10. Re1 $14 {White enjoys a slight but stable advantage.}
) 5. Nbd2 $1 {This move is going to be my main suggestion. White is
sacrificing the b2-pawn for long-term compensation.} (5. Qc1 $1 {SUPER SOS!! ..
..THIS IS PLAYABLE AND GOOD..BUT YOU KNEED TO AVOID SOME TARPS BY BLACK! ...
YOU NEED TO KNOW WHAT YOU ARE DOING! ...GENERALLY, OUR PLAN IS A FAST Nbd2-Rb1.
.and the queen back to d1 !!} Nc6 {Black should try to develop the queenside
as soon as possible. The idea is to create an opposition on the c-file by
means of ...d7-d5 followed by ...Bd7 and ...Rc8.} ({Weak is} 5... h6 $2 {
in view of} 6. Bxf6 gxf6 7. c4 $16 ({or} 7. d5 $1 $16 f5 8. c4 Bg7 9. Nc3 $16 {
In both cases, White has a considerable advantage since the black king will be
permanently vulnerable.})) 6. c3 d5 (6... Ne4 7. Bf4 $1 {SUPER SOS! ...USUALLY
OUR BISHOP RETREATS TO f4 IN THESE LINES!!!..NOT TO h4} cxd4 8. exd4 {White
has an advantage. He is ready to proceed with Bd3 followed by 0-0.}) ({White's
idea is very well illustrated by the following line:} 6... Be7 7. Nbd2 d5 8.
Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 10. Rb1 $1 {Remember that this move is an essential part of
White's strategy. Now, the queen is ready to leave the unfavourable c1-square.}
Rac8 11. Qd1 {[%cal Gf3e5] right on time! White is now ready to follow with
the thematic Ne5.} ({In this concrete case, the immediate} 11. Ne5 $1 {is
possible as well.} Qc7 $2 (11... Rfd8 12. Qd1 $16 (12. Qe1 $1 $16)) 12. f4 $16
{White has a big advantage.})) 7. Bd3 $1 {The development of the kingside
should be our priority.} (7. Nbd2 $2 {SUPER SOS....BE VERY VERY AWARE OF THIS
TYPICAL MISTAKE!!} cxd4 $3 8. exd4 e5 $1 {EVERYTHING DEPENDS ON THIS TACTICK! .
..PLEASE, LEARN TO AVOID IT!!} (8... h6 9. Bf4 e5 10. Bxe5) 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. Bh4
Bc5 {Black is already winning.}) 7... Bd7 {Black should play ...Rc8 as soon as
possible.} ({Alternatively, it's possible to start with} 7... h6 8. Bf4 $1 Bd7
9. Nbd2 Rc8 ({After} 9... Be7 {White can afford to secure the f4-bishop by
means of} 10. h3 Rc8 11. a3 $1 $14 {Another typical prophylactic move,
neutralizing the idea of ...cxd4 followed by ...Nb4.}) 10. a4 $5 {to avoid all
the Bb5 ideas!} ({Nevertheless, even after} 10. O-O cxd4 11. exd4 Nb4 12. Be2
Bb5 13. Bxb5+ Qxb5 14. Ne5 $132 {White has good attacking prospects on the
kingside.}) 10... cxd4 ({A typical reaction to} 10... Nh5 {is} 11. Be5 Nxe5 12.
dxe5 $14 {Besides providing a considerable space advantage, the e5-pawn
restricts the black knight as well.} ({Another possibility is} 12. Nxe5 {
[%cal Gf2f4] Later, White will follow with f2-f4.})) 11. exd4 Nb4 12. Be2 {
We can now see the point behind a2-a4. Black does not have the idea of ...Bb5.}
Nh5 13. Be3 $14 {with a stable advantage for White since Black does not have
concrete counterplay.}) ({Now, the typical} 7... cxd4 8. exd4 e5 {does not
work in view of} 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. O-O {It's now clear why we first developed
the kingside.}) 8. Nbd2 Rc8 9. a3 {White is slightly better since Black will
run out of dynamic resources.}) ({Inferior is} 5. Na3 $2 d5 {when our knight
is completely misplaced on a3.} 6. Bf4 (6. Nb5 a6) (6. Rb1 Ne4) 6... a6 {
Parrying the threat of Nb5. It's not clear what our knight is doing on a3.})
5... Qxb2 {The most principled continuation. There is no other way to justify
the move ...Qb6.} (5... d5 $6 6. Bxf6 $5 {This is the simplest. The black king
will be permanently weak now.} ({The alternative} 6. Rb1 $5 {is possible as
well.} Nc6 7. c3 h6 ({The seemingly aggressive} 7... Ne4 {is not dangerous at
all. White even has a choice.} 8. Nxe4 {In Torre, this is often a thematic
reaction to ...Ne4.} ({Additionally, the slow} 8. Bf4 {is perfectly playable
as well. For example, after} Be7 9. Bd3 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. O-O cxd4 12. exd4
{White achieves a thematic advantage since Black played ...d7-d5 and ...cxd4
which is never a good idea.}) 8... dxe4 9. Nd2 {White has an obvious advantage.
}) 8. Bh4 Be7 9. Bd3 a5 $6 {This move is dubious since it creates a hole on
the b5-square. White should play} 10. a4 $1 {preventing Black from winning
further queenside space and increasing the control of the b5-square.} O-O 11.
O-O c4 $6 {A typical mistake in this pawn structure. Since there is no longer
tension in the centre, White has a free hand in the centre and on the kingside.
} 12. Bc2 Qc7 {Black is trying to take the control of the e5-square.} ({After} 
12... Bd7 {White can play} 13. Ne5 Qc7 (13... Nxe5 $2 {is dropping a piece
after} 14. dxe5 $18) 14. f4 Rac8 15. g4 $18 {White has a winning kingside
attack.}) 13. Qe2 ({An alternative is} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. e4 b6 15. Re1 $1 (15.
e5) 15... Bb7 16. Qe2 Rfe8 17. e5 Be7 18. Nf1 $16 {Once again, White enjoys a
free attack on the kingside. At the same time, Black has no counterplay
whatsoever.}) 13... Nd7 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. e4 $16 {White enjoyed a huge
advantage in the game 1-0 (54) Wolf, U (2189)-Faqiry, R (2013) Bad Homburg 2016
}) 6... gxf6 7. dxc5 Qxb2 8. c4 $16 {Just like in the main line, White has a
long-term compensation based on Black's vulnerable king. A possible line is}
dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bxc5 10. O-O O-O 11. Rb1 Qa3 12. Rb5 $1 {Remember this idea. In
this pawn structure, the rook lift on the 5th rank is very typical.} Be7 13.
Rh5 $16 {The kingside attack is very dangerous.}) 6. Bd3 $1 {This is the most
flexible move order.} ({Nevertheless, a very decent alternative is} 6. Bxf6 $5
gxf6 7. Bd3 {Practically speaking, White's play is a lot easier.} d5 ({The
alternative} 7... cxd4 {does not manage to solve the problems. After} 8. exd4
d5 9. O-O Qb6 10. c4 {White enjoys his typical long-term compensation.}) 8. c4
dxc4 9. Bxc4 cxd4 10. exd4 $44) 6... d5 ({After} 6... Qb6 $6 7. Bxf6 gxf6 8.
O-O $40 {White gets the type of compensation he is aiming for. Practically
speaking, it's very difficult to play this position for Black.} d5 $2 ({
If Black decides to refrain from ...d7-d5, we have the following thematic idea
-} 8... Bg7 9. Rb1 Qc7 10. d5 $3 {By means of this typical pawn sacrifice,
White wants to weaken the f5-square.} O-O (10... exd5 11. Nh4 $16) 11. e4 $16
d6 12. Nh4 Nd7 13. f4 $16 {with a very strong attack. Black is completely
busted.}) 9. c4 $16 cxd4 10. exd4 ({The alternative} 10. Nxd4 {gives
compensation as well.})) ({Black can also try to prevent the appearance of
doubled pawns by means of} 6... Be7 7. O-O d5 ({It's important to mention that
after} 7... O-O $2 8. e4 $18 {[%cal Ge4e5] White has a winning advantage in
view of the advance e4-e5 that is coming on the next move.}) 8. c4 $44 O-O 9.
cxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 {It turns out that Black cannot win a pawn without
accepting positional concessions. For example, after} Bxc5 $2 11. Rb1 Qc3 12.
Rb3 Qa5 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Nh4 $18 {White has a winning attack.}) 7. Bxf6 gxf6
8. c4 $36 {This is the kind of position we are looking for. Playing with Black
is practically very difficult. The following lines confirm this evaluation.}
cxd4 (8... Qb6 $2 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Rb1 Qd8 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. O-O Nc6 13. Qa4
$16 (13. Nb3 $16)) 9. exd4 $5 (9. Rb1 $5 Qa3 10. Rb3 Qa5 11. Nxd4 $36) 9... Qa3
10. Qe2 $36 *

