{[%evp 0,45,17,20,20,16,16,21,25,2,28,26,54,30,25,20,19,17,20,-4,-6,-6,-5,-2,
79,50,102,49,73,49,66,29,106,74,91,91,578,576,1482,1658,1729,1815,29995,29996,
29997,29998,29999,-30000] From this game, we start dealing with the so-called
Miladinovic System against the Hedgehog setup. This is a rare and aggressive
variation that will probably surprise your opponent. Even though this is an
online game, White managed to execute some of the most thematic ideas.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 b6 {With this move, Black indicates
his intention to play in a Hedgehog style.} ({Of course, different move orders
are possible. Black can also start with} 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 b6 {Usually, Black
plays this move before ...d7-d6.} ({It is very important to remember that in
case of} 6... d6 {we should immediately take the knight -} 7. Bxf6 {The idea
is to force Black to recapture with the bishop. If White waits for one more
move, Black will be in time to play ...Nbd7.} Bxf6 8. Bd3 Nd7 9. Qe2 O-O {
As we are going to witness on many occasions, this move is premature against
Miladinovic System. White immediately plays} 10. O-O-O {[%cal Gh2h4] In
general, White's attack is very quick in this setup. Let's take a look at some
sample lines -} b6 11. c3 Bb7 12. h4 $1 {This is a key move in White's
attacking concept. Black should now always reckon with moves such as Bxh7 and
Ng5.} Rc8 ({Against} 12... a6 {besides all other promising moves, White can
also consider} 13. Bxh7+ {This sacrifice should always be backed up with
precise calculation.} Kxh7 14. Ng5+ Kh6 {The most tenacious defence. Other
moves are losing on the spot.} ({After} 14... Bxg5 $2 15. hxg5+ Kg8 16. Qh5 f5
17. g6 {Black will get checkmated.}) ({Typically bad defence is} 14... Kg8 15.
Qh5 Re8 16. Qxf7+ Kh8 17. Rh3 {when White is attacking basically for free.} (
17. Rde1)) 15. Qe3 Qe7 16. Nc4 $16 {[%cal Gc4d6] This resource makes the
entire difference. The threat is Nxd6.}) 13. Kb1 {Here is the sacrifice on h7
does not work since we don't have the resource of Nc4 in the main line.} Be7
14. Ne4 {In this structure, e4 is a very nice square for the knight. Black
cannot challenge our knight without committing serious positional concessions.
For example, if he plays ...d6-d5, then we get our favourite type of structure
- ...cxd4 in a combination with ...d7-d5. If Black plays} Nf6 {White can
immediately go for} 15. Nxf6+ {By exchanging the black knight, we drastically
reduce Black's dynamic resources.} ({Another decent option is} 15. Nfg5) 15...
Bxf6 16. g4 {White's kingside attack is very dangerous. At the same time, it's
not clear how Black will create counterplay.}) {Since Black has not played ...
d7-d6 yet, White can afford to wait with the move Bxf6.} 7. Bd3 ({Nevertheless,
the lazy approach would be the immediate} 7. Bxf6) 7... Bb7 ({After} 7... d6 {
we are forced to go for} 8. Bxf6) 8. c3 {In this redaction, you need to reckon
with} Nd5 {The game might continue} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 {with
slight but stable advantage for White. Compared to the Miladinovic System,
however, now the play is much more positional.}) 6. Nbd2 Bb7 7. Bd3 Be7 ({
An obvious alternative is} 7... h6 {When Black can recapture on f6 with the
queen, I prefer} 8. Bh4 ({The computer, however, tends to like} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9.
Qe2 {with 0-0-0 to follow. With a queen on f6, however, I am somewhat worried
on a possible counterplay based on ...g7-g5.}) 8... Be7 {Now, when Black will
be forced to recapture with the bishop, we can go for our usual setup -} 9.
Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qe2 O-O 11. O-O-O Nc6 12. c3 Rc8 13. Kb1 {Once again, we have
reached the standard position of the Miladinovic System. The inclusion of the
move ...h7-h6 is favourable for White since the h6-pawn is a hook that speeds
up White's attack.}) 8. c3 O-O ({As always, the move} 8... d6 {will be
answered with} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qe2 Nd7 11. O-O-O Be7 ({It's important to now
how to handle the position arising after} 11... O-O 12. h4 e5 {This central
break seems logical since the flank attack is best countered by a strike in
the centre. In this case, however, Black only plays into White's hand. White
should react with} 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Ne4 {It transpires that the advance ...
e6-e5 gave a lot of nice squares to White's pieces. The e4-knight is extremely
powerful. After} Qe7 {, White can play either} 15. Nfg5 ({or} 15. g4 {In both
cases, with a strong attack.})) 12. Kb1 a6 13. h4 Nf6 14. Ka1 $1 {Remember
this resource. White is ready to answer ...0-0 with Bb1 followed by Qd3.} Nd5
15. g3 O-O 16. Bb1 b5 17. Qd3 g6 18. h5 {White enjoys a powerful attack.}) 9.
Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qe2 d6 11. O-O-O e5 {We already know that this break does not
solve Black's problems. White immediately went for the thematic} 12. dxe5 dxe5
13. Ne4 Nc6 14. h4 {The kingside pawn expansion is the most common way to
attack in the Miladinovic System.} Qe7 15. g4 g6 16. h5 {White wants to open
the kingside as soon as possible.} ({Another decent possibility would have been
} 16. g5 Bg7 17. h5 {White's attack is overwhelming. The game might continue
with} Rac8 18. Kb1 Rfd8 19. hxg6 fxg6 (19... hxg6 20. Rh4 $18 (20. Nh2 $18 {
[%cal Gh2g4]})) 20. Bc4+ {when White is winning.}) 16... Bg7 ({Of course, the
move} 16... g5 {is a huge concession. White can play either} 17. h6 ({or} 17.
Ng3 {with a huge advantage.})) 17. hxg6 fxg6 (17... hxg6 18. g5 $18) 18. Bc4+
Kh8 19. Rxh7+ Kxh7 20. Nfg5+ Kh8 21. Rh1+ Bh6 22. Rxh6+ Kg7 23. Rh7# 1-0

