{Now, we shall examine a very thematic game for the Miladinovic System against
the Hedgehog. White got some initiative by trading the light-squared bishops..
and putting the knight on d3!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4
Be7 6. c3 {This is the traditional move order. The lazy man' approach would be
to take on f6 immediately. We can afford to take the knight always when Black
is forced to recapture with the bishop.} b6 ({Note that after} 6... d6 {
[%cal Gb8d7] planning ...Nbd7, we are forced to take on f6 immediately -} 7.
Bxf6 {A possible follow up will be} Bxf6 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge1c1]
After Qe2 followed by 0-0-0, White is planning to organize a kingside attack.}
(9. d5 e5) 9... O-O (9... Nd7 10. Qe2 Nf6 11. h4 a6 12. O-O-O (12. a4 b6) 12...
b5 {We will take a look at this approach a bit later.})) 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. Bxf6 {
White decides to start with this move before playing Qe2. In this way, he
rules out any ...Nd5 based ideas.} Bxf6 9. Qe2 d6 10. Nbd2 Nd7 11. h4 {With
this move, White is discouraging his opponent to castle short.} ({The most
common type of position in the Miladinovic System would arise after} 11. O-O-O
O-O 12. h4 {Now, ideas such as Bxh7 and Ng5 are always in the air.
Additionally, the e4-square is a very nice springboard for the d2-knight. In
this specific case, the e4-square is just like a stronghold since the advance .
..d6-d5 is structurally undesirable. We should also mention, that in all these
positions, computer advocates Bc2 followed by Qd3.}) 11... Be7 12. Ne4 {
As mentioned above, putting the knight on e4 is always a good idea in this
pawn structure.} Qc7 13. O-O-O h6 {The idea of this waiting move is to take
the control of the g5-square. When the move ...h7-h6 is included, it becomes
clear that Black is planning to castle long.} ({Another interesting line would
be} 13... a6 {depriving White of Bb5+ before playing ...Nf6.} 14. Kb1 Nf6 15.
Nxf6+ $3 {The most precise move. By exchanging the remaining the f6-knight,
White restricts Black's dynamic resources. Another favourable idea would be to
exchange the light-squared bishops and build a white square strategy by using
the powerful tandem queen + knight.} Bxf6 16. g4 $16 {Immediately gaining
space on the kingside. Having played ...a7-a6, Black has now problems finding
safe heaven for his king.} Be7 17. g5 b5 18. Rhg1 $16 Bd5 ({The alternative} 
18... g6 {is well met by} 19. h5) 19. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4] freeing the way of
the f-pawn.} ({Of course, White can keep gaining space with} 19. h5 $16 {
when a possible line would be} h6 20. gxh6 gxh6 21. Nd2 $16 Qb7 22. f4 {
It's not clear how Black will take care of his king. The advance f4-f5 is on
the agenda.})) ({White's strategy remains unchanged after} 13... Nf6 14. Nxf6+
Bxf6 15. g4 $16 h6 16. Kb1 O-O-O 17. Ba6 $16 {After exchanging a pair of
knights, White also wants to exchange the light-squared bishops. The remaining
Black bishop will be completely useless in this pawn structure.}) 14. Kb1 O-O-O
({A very characteristic line for this setup would be} 14... a6 15. g4 b5 16. g5
Nb6 17. g6 O-O 18. gxf7+ Rxf7 19. Nfg5 $18 {when White is winning.}) 15. g4 $5
$14 {Even though there is nothing wrong with this thematic move, I would
definitely prefer exchanging the light-squared bishops via a6.} ({Let's take a
look at how the game can develop after} 15. Ba6 $1 {A logical reaction would be
} d5 16. Ned2 Bxa6 17. Qxa6+ Qb7 18. Qe2 $1 {This is an important move. We
should try to keep the queens since very often we get a position with queen
and knight vs queen and bishop.} Bd6 ({After} 18... Kb8 {White can immediately
go for an exchange of the knights after} 19. Ne5) 19. h5 {I like this move
that fixes Black's kingside structure.} Nf6 20. Ne5 Kb8 21. f4 {We can now see
the drawbacks of the advance ...d6-d5. White's control of the e5-square gives
him a huge advantage.} ({Usually, before playing f2-f4, we need to take
control of the e4-square. Therefore, another possibility would be} 21. Rde1 $16
{when the structural transformation arising after} Bxe5 (21... Rc8 22. f4) 22.
dxe5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd2b3,Gb3d4] is favourable for White. He can now follow
with Nb3-d4.} Nd7 23. Nb3 Nc5 24. Nd4 a6 25. Rh4 $16 {[%cal Gh4g4] Remember
this thematic positional idea. After fixing the g7-pawn by means of h4-h5,
White prepares Rg4.} b5 26. Rg4 {White enjoys a big positional advantage.}) {
In this concrete position, the thematic} 21... Ne4 {does not work well in view
of} 22. Nxe4 dxe4 23. g4 f6 24. Ng6 $16 {The weakness of the g6-square is
making the entire difference. The game might continue with} Rhe8 25. Rhe1 f5
26. gxf5 exf5 27. Qb5 Qc8 28. a4 $16 {White enjoys full domination.}) 15... Nf6
{White's reaction to this move is quite thematic -} 16. Nxf6 Bxf6 17. Ba6 $1
$16 Bxa6 18. Qxa6+ Qb7 19. Qe2 $16 d5 {This advance usually leads to a pawn
structure that is favourable for White. On the other hand, if Black refrains
from it, White can often play d4-d5 himself.} ({After} 19... Kb8 {a possible
line would be} 20. Rhe1 ({Fixing the kingside structure with} 20. h5 {is
always a possibility.}) 20... Rhe8 21. a3 $16 g6 22. g5 Bg7 23. d5 $1 {With a
pawn on d6, Black should always consider this thematic break.} e5 24. Nd4 $18)
20. Ne1 $1 $16 {[%cal Ge1d3] In Carlsbad structure, d3 is a magic square for
the knight. From this position, the knight practically controls the entire
board.} Be7 21. Nd3 ({An even more technical solution would have been to first
fix the kingside structure with} 21. h5 $5 {with the following possible line -}
Bd6 22. Nd3 Rhe8 23. f4 f6 24. Rde1 {Black has no counterplay whatsoever. The
d3-knight is preventing all the possible pawn breaks. Now, White will
gradually start preparing the advance g4-g5.} Kb8 25. Rhg1 a6 26. g5 $14) 21...
h5 22. g5 {This thematic move is enough for an advantage.} ({Even better would
be} 22. gxh5 $1 $16 {when White does not have any compensation for the pawn.})
22... g6 23. Rh3 Bd6 24. Rf3 Rhe8 25. Ne5 Bxe5 26. dxe5 (26. Qxe5 $14) 26...
Kb8 27. Rd4 Rd7 28. a4 Rc8 29. Rff4 Rc5 30. Qe3 Qc6 31. Qf3 Qc7 32. Qe2 Qb7 33.
Rf6 Qc6 34. Qf3 Qb7 35. Rdf4 Rcc7 36. a5 $2 bxa5 37. Ka1 Qb3 (37... Qb5 $17)
38. Rxf7 Rb7 39. Rf8+ Kc7 40. Qe2 a4 41. R8f7 a3 42. Rxd7+ Kxd7 43. Rf7+ Kc8
44. Rf8+ Kd7 45. Rf7+ Kc8 1/2-1/2

