{[%evp 0,63,25,37,38,26,24,13,30,-11,6,10,0,8,38,20,20,16,16,10,24,11,18,3,7,
-1,22,0,21,27,23,-21,0,1,8,5,8,-1,22,23,25,34,46,40,49,36,36,35,35,22,22,-30,
28,20,43,21,39,29,40,50,395,433,406,409,504,492] This game is a very good
illustration of how White should handle the Miladinovic System when Black goes
for a long castle.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 h6 4. Bh4 c5 5. e3 cxd4 6. exd4
b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. Qe2 $5 {It's much smpler to just take on f6..and
then go for Qe2!} ({For example, after} 9. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 10. Qe2 Nc6 11. c3 O-O
12. O-O-O {we immediately get a normal position for the Miladinovic System.})
9... Nc6 ({Probably, Black should have tried} 9... Nd5 $1 10. Bg3 Nb4 {when
White will obviously part with his light-squared bishop.}) 10. c3 Nh5 ({
At this point, the move} 10... Nd5 {can be met by the thematic} 11. Bg3 {
White can even castle short. It's not easy at all for Black to obtain
counterplay in this position.}) 11. Bg3 $1 {This is a wise choice by Kramnik.
The thing is that after} Nxg3 12. hxg3 {White actually improves his pawn
structure. For Black is already very dangerous to castle short in view of the
idea g3-g4-g5.} Qc7 13. O-O-O O-O-O {A logical choice by Karpov. Now, at least
his king will be safe. At this point, White has two major ideas: 1) exchange
the light-squared bishops and transfer his knight to d3 (we are going to
witness this plan in one of the model games) 2) initiate a kingside play by
means of g3-g4 It's important to point out, that these two ideas do not
exclude each other.} 14. Kb1 Kb8 15. g4 Qf4 16. Ne1 d5 17. g3 Qd6 18. f4 g5 19.
Ng2 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gf3e5,Gh1h5,Gd1h1] White already has a huge advantage. He can
double his rooks along the h-file and bring the knight to e5. Kramnik
eventually managed to win a nice game.} Rdg8 20. Rh5 f6 21. Rdh1 Bf8 22. Nf3
Bg7 23. Re1 Re8 24. Bb5 Re7 25. Qd3 Nd8 26. Rhh1 Rf8 27. Re2 Bc8 28. Rhe1 Nf7
29. Ne3 Rd8 30. Nf5 exf5 31. Rxe7 fxg4 32. Rxf7 1-0

