{[%evp 0,125,24,24,24,29,26,12,16,15,88,54,72,56,61,66,85,19,64,60,71,68,67,47,
65,63,57,50,46,36,41,32,59,55,48,46,48,47,45,32,45,39,56,39,46,45,38,47,45,38,
67,43,9,9,9,9,-11,-18,-12,-33,-35,-33,-15,0,10,-36,5,0,-7,-44,0,0,0,0,0,-8,0,0,
0,0,0,0,76,61,76,75,94,105,98,84,84,62,62,60,61,95,93,66,111,111,94,101,99,71,
67,58,55,10,0,28,32,48,40,50,42,49,42,-67,-67,-52,-58,-107,-94,-159,-158,-174,
29999,-30000] At the end, we shall take a look at one very typical mistake
that Black often commits. Even a player like the former World Champion Anatoly
Karpov has made this mistake twice! The position of interest arises after the
moves} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 b6 $2 {This move leads by force to
a very big positional advantage for White. If Black wants to go for this setup,
he should combine this move with either ...h7-h6 or ...cxd4. The point is that
now White has} 5. d5 $1 {It turns out that White wins the battle for the
d5-square. This pawn advance in the centre seizes a lot of space and hinders
the development of the black pieces.} h6 ({An important alternative is} 5...
exd5 {You should memorize a few moves in this line. Nevertheless, the reward
for your work will be considerable - White is getting a serious advantage by
force!} 6. Nc3 Bb7 7. Nxd5 $1 {It's important to start with this move.} Be7 ({
The alternative} 7... Bxd5 {does not help either. The game might follow} 8.
Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxd5 {The control of the important d5-square provides White with
a huge advantage.} Nc6 {Black should settle for this move.} ({After} 9... Qxb2
$2 10. Rd1 Qc3+ 11. Rd2 Qa1+ 12. Ke2 $18 {White is winning.}) 10. c3 Be7 11.
Bc4 {Playing a middlegame with opposite-coloured bishops is my preference in
this case.} ({Nevertheless, a decent alternative is} 11. Bb5 Rd8 12. O-O O-O
13. Rad1 Rfe8 14. Bxc6 dxc6 15. Qe5 {when White is forcing the transition into
a favourable endgame.}) 11... Rd8 12. O-O O-O 13. Rad1 {White has a big
positional advantage.}) 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. c3 O-O 10. Bc4 $16 {The control of the
d5-square gives White a big advantage.}) 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. Nc3 a6 8. e4 {When we
have superiority in the centre, Black's queenside counterplay is completely
meaningless. Black should probably close the centre with} e5 ({After} 8... b5
9. e5 Qd8 10. a4 b4 11. Ne4 Bb7 12. Bc4 {White has a decisive advantage.}) 9.
a4 {Now, when we don't have play in the centre, we should prevent Black from
expanding on the queenside. This pawn structure is very typical for the
so-called Schmid Benoni. White's biggest advantage is that his pawn is on c2,
instead of c4. In this case, the c4-square is available for the knight.
Therefore, White executes the manoeuvre Nd2-c4 as soon as possible.} d6 10. Nd2
Nd7 11. Nc4 g6 12. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1h3] Sjugirov is planning to proceed with
h2-h4 followed by Bh3. In this pawn structure, the exchange of the
light-squared bishops is one of White's major positional ideas.} Rb8 13. h4 {
White is not afraid of ...b6-b5. This advance can be answered with axb5
followed by Na5. In this way, White will make use of the weak c6-square.} h5
14. Bh3 $16 {White is clearly better. Sjugirov managed to convert his
advantage.} Bg7 15. Kf1 Qe7 16. Kg2 O-O 17. Qe2 Nf6 18. Bxc8 Rfxc8 19. Ne3 Ra8
20. Rhb1 Nd7 21. Qd3 Bh6 22. Nc4 Rab8 23. Na3 Ra8 24. Rf1 Rf8 25. Rab1 f5 26.
exf5 gxf5 27. Qe2 Qf7 28. Nc4 Qg6 29. Kh2 Rab8 30. Rg1 Nf6 31. f3 Nd7 32. Na3
Ra8 33. Nc4 Kh8 34. Qd3 Kh7 35. Rbf1 Rab8 36. Na3 Ra8 37. Nc4 Rf7 38. Kh1 Rg8
39. Na3 Ra8 40. Nc4 Rg7 41. g4 hxg4 42. fxg4 fxg4 43. Qxg6+ Rxg6 44. Rf7+ Rg7
45. Rxg7+ Bxg7 46. Rxg4 Nf6 47. Rg1 b5 48. Nxd6 b4 49. Nce4 Nxd5 50. Nf5 Bh6
51. Rd1 Ne3 52. Rd7+ Kg6 53. Nfg3 Bf4 54. h5+ Kh6 55. Rd6+ Kh7 56. Rd7+ Kh6 57.
Rd6+ Kh7 58. h6 c4 59. Nh5 Bxh6 60. Nhf6+ Kg6 61. Ng4+ Kf5 62. Ngf2 Bf4 63.
Rf6# 1-0

