1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 h6 4. Bxf6 $5 {This is a move for lazy players who
wants to avoid the main theoretical battles. The arising positions are
suitable for Black. In my opinion, White has only one idea of fighting for an
advantage. This is the idea a4-a5, trying to fix the queenside and limit
Black's counterplay. That way White can hope for a long-term advantage.} Qxf6
5. e4 d6 6. c3 (6. Nc3 {is possible, but this is not a very good system.} Nd7
7. Nb5 {is not working due to} (7. Be2 g5 $1) 7... Qd8) 6... Nd7 (6... g6 7. a4
Bg7 8. a5 O-O 9. Nbd2 a6 (9... Nd7 10. a6 $1 $14) 10. Bc4 c5 11. dxc5 $3 (11.
e5) 11... dxc5 12. Qe2 (12. e5 $6 Qe7 13. O-O Nc6 14. Qe2 Qc7 15. Rfe1 Nxa5 $15
) 12... Nc6 13. Bb3 Ne5 (13... Bd7 14. Nc4) (13... Qd8 14. Nc4) 14. Nxe5 Qxe5
15. Nc4 Qc7 16. Nb6 Rb8 17. Ba4 $3 (17. Qe3) 17... e5 18. Bb3 $16) (6... a6 7.
Nbd2 g6 8. Bd3 Bg7 9. e5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12. f4 $14) (6... b6 $2
{is a mistake, but you can see this system in the next games.}) 7. a4 $1 {
Is the best idea in this position} (7. Nbd2 $5 g6 8. Bd3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1
e5 11. Nc4 Qe7 {The g7-bishop is very strong and without opposition, Black can
be better in a long-term} 12. dxe5 dxe5 (12... Nxe5 13. Ncxe5 dxe5 {Black is
excellent})) 7... g5 (7... a5 $1 {this is probably the best continuation for
Black} 8. Na3 $1 {The knight is going to "c4" or "b5"} g6 9. h4 (9. Bd3 Bg7 10.
O-O O-O 11. Re1 Qd8 12. Nc4 d5) 9... Bg7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. Nb5 Qd8 12. Bc2 e5 13.
h5 g5) (7... g6 8. a5 {[%cal Ra5a6]} a6 {Black should stop a5-a6 and now the
structure is fixed} 9. Nbd2 Bg7 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O e5 (11... c5 {[%csl Ra6,
Rb7]}) 12. Re1) 8. Na3 Bg7 9. a5 a6 10. Nc4 Qe7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O $16 {
All of a sudden, White is better. The reason is very deep! ...one by one,
black has lost all his pawn breaks! For example, f7-f5 weakens the position.
The break e6-e5 loses the f5 square. The d6-d5 is not good either, because
after ed5-ed5, Black weakens the f5-square. And if c7-c5, Black is self-fixed
on the queenside. The last option is the break b5, but after axb6 Black is
still full of weaknesses! I find the idea a4-a5 very impressive and deep.} e5
13. Ne3 $16 {White is already better. I leave the rest of the game without
comments.} (13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nfxe5 dxe5 15. Ne3 Be6 16. Bc4 $16 {If we
exchange the light-squared bishops, then White will be better.}) 13... Nf6 14.
Re1 Re8 15. Bc2 Qf8 16. d5 c6 17. c4 Rb8 18. Nd2 Bd7 19. Ndf1 Rec8 20. Ng3 Qd8
21. b3 b5 22. axb6 Rxb6 23. Qd2 Rcb8 24. Ra3 Bc8 25. Nef5 Bf8 26. Qe2 Nd7 27.
Qh5 Qf6 28. h4 Nc5 29. Re3 Qg6 30. Qg4 f6 31. Rf3 a5 32. Kh2 a4 33. bxa4 Rb2
34. Rfc3 Kh7 35. a5 gxh4 36. Qxh4 Qg5 37. Qxg5 hxg5 38. dxc6 Kg6 39. Ne3 Na6
40. Nd5 Nb4 41. Rab3 Nxc6 42. Rxb8 Rxb8 43. Bd1 g4 44. Ra3 Ra8 45. Nb6 Rb8 46.
Nxc8 Rxc8 47. Bxg4 Ra8 48. a6 d5 49. Bf5+ Kf7 50. Ra4 Nb4 51. cxd5 Rxa6 52.
Rxa6 Nxa6 53. Be6+ Kg6 54. Kh3 Nc5 55. Kg4 Nd3 56. Kf3 Nf4 57. Nf5 Bb4 58. g3
Nh3 59. Nh4+ Kg7 60. Bxh3 Kf8 61. Be6 Ke7 62. Nf5+ Kf8 63. Kg4 Bc5 64. f3 Bf2
65. Kh5 Be1 66. Kg6 Bc3 67. Kxf6 Ba1 68. d6 Bc3 69. Ne7 Ba1 70. Bf7 Bc3 71.
Ng6# 1-0

