{Another example of the Bxf6 idea, connected with a4! This time, Black was
more careful to play g6 instead of g5. Now the f5-square is not weak ..so on
the move 12 he could go for e5 as he did, or for 12...d5!? With a good play.
The g6 pawn in every case covers the f5-square} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 h6
4. Bxf6 Qxf6 5. e4 d6 (5... d5 $6 {this is not a good idea. White can keep the
tension and push e4-e5 in an appropriate moment.} 6. Nbd2 g6 7. c3 Bg7 8. e5
Qe7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. h4 Nd7 11. h5 g5) 6. c3 Nd7 7. a4 g6 8. Na3 (8. a5) 8... a6
9. a5 Bg7 10. Nc4 Qe7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O e5 (12... g5 13. Re1 e5 $16 {[%csl
Rf5][%cal Rc4e3]} (13... c5 14. e5 $1 d5 (14... dxe5 15. dxe5 $16) 15. Nd6 $16)
) (12... d5 13. exd5 exd5 14. Re1 Qd8 15. Ne3 Nf6 $132) 13. Re1 Re8 14. Rc1 Rb8
(14... exd4 15. cxd4 Nf6 16. e5 dxe5 17. Ncxe5 $14 (17. Nfxe5)) (14... Nf8 15.
dxe5 dxe5 16. Ne3 c6 (16... Be6 17. Bc4 $1 $14) 17. Nc4 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7,Rc6]
}) 15. Bf1 Nf8 16. Ne3 Qd8 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Qb3 Be6 19. Bc4 $14 c6 20. Qa3 (
20. Bxe6 Nxe6 21. Nc4 Nc5 22. Qc2 Nd3 $4 (22... Qd3 $1 23. Nfd2 h5 (23... Rbd8
$11)) 23. Red1 $18) 20... Qc7 21. Rcd1 Rbd8 22. b4 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Rd8 24. Qa1 h5
25. g3 Bh6 26. Bxe6 Nxe6 27. Nc4 f6 28. Qb1 Bf8 29. Rd3 Kf7 30. Qd1 Rxd3 31.
