{another blitz game between two extremely strong players....this time with a
delayed cd4 by black..which is typically answered with cd4! ..and some slight
but annoying pressure!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. c3 h6 5. Bh4 b6 6. e3
Bb7 7. Nbd2 {Remember we develop the knights before the bishops} Be7 8. Bd3 Nc6
9. a3 O-O 10. O-O cxd4 (10... d5 11. Ne5 {we should consider this move now
with the idea to take on f6 and to play f4.} (11. Qe2 {Is another option} cxd4
$2 (11... Nd7 12. Bg3 $14 {and White has a small but stable advantage.}) 12.
exd4 Nh5 13. Bg3 $16 (13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qe3)) 11... Rc8 $2 (11... Nxe5 $1 12.
dxe5 Ne4 13. Bxe7 {a possible line is} Qxe7 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Qg4 Qg5 16. Qxg5
hxg5 17. Rfd1) 12. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 13. f4 Qe7 14. Qh5 $16 {and White is
strategically winning.}) 11. cxd4 $5 {This move is very unpleasant for Black,
because it leaves him without counterplay.} (11. exd4 {Is also possible, but
Black is doing more or less fine after:} Nh5 12. Bg3 (12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Re1)
12... Nxg3 13. hxg3) 11... Rc8 12. Qe2 Nh5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Rac1 Nf6 15. Rc2 {
Typical plan. White is slightly better and Carlsen manages to convert it to a
nice win.} Nb8 16. Rfc1 Rxc2 17. Rxc2 Rc8 18. Rxc8+ Bxc8 19. e4 Bb7 20. e5 Nh7
21. Nc4 Nf8 22. Nd6 Bxf3 23. Qxf3 Nc6 24. Qe4 f5 25. Qe3 Qh4 26. f4 g5 27. g3
gxf4 28. gxf4 Ng6 29. Qg3 Kh7 30. d5 Nce7 31. dxe6 dxe6 32. Qxh4 Nxh4 33. Bc4
Nhg6 34. Bxe6 Nxf4 35. Bxf5+ Nxf5 36. Nxf5 Kg6 37. Nd6 Nd3 38. Nc8 Nxe5 39.
Nxa7 Nc4 40. Nc8 b5 41. Na7 Nxb2 42. Nxb5 Kf5 43. Kg2 h5 44. Kg3 Kg5 45. Nc3
Nc4 46. a4 Na5 47. Ne4+ Kg6 48. Kf4 Nc4 49. Nc5 Na5 50. h4 Kf6 51. Ne4+ Kg6 52.
Ng3 Nb7 53. Ke3 Nd6 54. Kd4 Nb7 55. Kc4 Kf6 56. Kb4 Ke5 57. Nxh5 Kf5 58. Ng3+
1-0

