1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 b6 $2 {is a well-known mistake.} (4... h6
5. Bh4 b6 6. d5 $2 g5) 5. c3 $2 (5. d5 $1 $16 {Is the strongest move, with a
big advantage for White.}) 5... Bb7 6. Bd3 Be7 7. Nbd2 O-O (7... cxd4 8. exd4 {
If the king is still on e1, we should take with the e-pawn. Later takes on f6
and plays Qe2 followed by 0-0-0} O-O 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qe2 $14) 8. O-O d6 (8...
h6 9. Bh4 a6 (9... d5 10. Ne5) 10. Qe2 (10. Ne5 d6) (10. e4) 10... cxd4 (10...
d5 11. Ne5 Nc6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. f4) 11. exd4 Nh5 12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3) (8...
cxd4 9. cxd4 $1 {I prefer to take with the c-pawn when Black delays cxd4.} (9.
exd4 d6 {I think that Black is fine in this position}) 9... Nc6 {Black doesn't
have any counterplay in this position.} 10. a3 Rc8 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. Rac1 Qb8 {
Now White has various plans} 13. Rc2 {Followed by doubling the rooks on the
c-file.} ({Exchanging the light-squared bishops is also good for White.} 13.
Ba6 Bxa6 14. Qxa6) (13. e4 {Is the most ambitious way to handle the position.})
) (8... Nc6 {After this move White should continue with} 9. a3 $1 {Preparing
for cxd4} cxd4 10. cxd4 $14) 9. Qe2 $5 (9. e4 $5 {Is another good option} Nc6
10. a3 $1 h6 11. Bh4 Nh5 12. Bxe7 (12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 $14 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5
15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Nc4 $16) 12... Qxe7 13. Re1 Nf4 14. Bf1 cxd4 15. cxd4 e5 16.
g3 Ng6 17. Nc4 $14) 9... Nbd7 10. e4 (10. Rfe1 cxd4 11. exd4 h6 12. Bh4 Nh5 (
12... d5 $2 13. Ne5) (12... Nd5 13. Bg3) 13. Bg3 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Nf6 15. Rad1 (
15. Ne4 $6 Bxe4 16. Bxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4) 15... Qc7 16. Bb1 Rfe8 17. Nf1 (17. Qd3
) 17... Bf8 18. Ne3) 10... e5 {This position resembles the Torre Attack with
g6.} 11. dxe5 $1 dxe5 (11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 $1 dxe5 13. Nc4 ({The engines likes
} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Bc4 $14 {With an idea to maneuver the knight to d5.}) 13...
Qc7 {A possible line here is} 14. f3 Rad8 15. Ne3 h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Bc4 $1
Bg5 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 $16) 12. Rad1 (12. Rfd1 {Is possibly the better
continuation} Qc7 13. a4 h6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Bc4 Rfd8 16. Ne1 $14 {[%cal
Re1c2,Rc2e3] I consider this position, much better for White}) 12... Qc7 13.
Rfe1 Rfe8 14. Nf1 (14. Ba6 {Another typical idea is to exchange the
light-squared bishops which will leaves the light squares in Black's position
without protection.} Rad8 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Ne3 $16)
14... c4 15. Bxc4 Nxe4 16. Bxf7+ $3 Kh8 (16... Kxf7 17. Rxd7 $18) 17. Bxe8 Rxe8
18. Bxe7 Rxe7 19. Ng3 1-0

