{Another model game how White should face quick Be7 and 0-0} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
e6 3. Bg5 Be7 4. Nbd2 d5 5. e3 O-O (5... c5 {Is possible too} 6. c3 b6 7. Bb5+
(7. Ne5 {looks good too}) 7... Bd7 8. Bd3 {Is a very typical way of handling
White's position.}) 6. Bd3 Nbd7 7. c3 $1 c5 (7... h6 8. Bf4 {Intending Ne5}) 8.
Ne5 $1 h6 9. h4 $3 (9. Bf4 $1 {Is very strong too.} Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Qh5
f5 12. g4 $18) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4 f5 {Usually when we see f5, we
are not taking on f6.} 12. exf6 $5 (12. Qh5 $5 Qe8 13. Qxe8 Rxe8 14. Bxe7 Rxe7
15. h5 $3 {This is a wonderful strategical think. Later White will prepare g4.
White is much better. Black can't play d4 and c4 is not very good too.} c4 (
15... b6 16. g4 (16. Rg1 Bb7 17. g4 fxg4 18. Rxg4 c4 19. Bc2 Nc5 20. Nf3 $18)
16... fxg4 17. Rg1 Bb7 18. Rxg4 $16) 16. Bc2 Nc5 17. Rg1 Bd7 18. g4 fxg4 19.
Rxg4 b5 20. a3 (20. Ke2) 20... Be8 21. Rh4) 12... Bxf6 (12... Nxf6 $5 13. Bxf6
Bxf6 14. Qh5 $16 Qe8 15. Bg6 Qe7 16. g4 $18 e5 17. f5 {White is much better})
13. Nf3 $16 (13. Qh5 $16) 13... e5 14. Bc2 $3 d4 15. Qd3 Qb6 16. Qh7+ Kf7 17.
Qg6+ $6 (17. fxe5 $3 Qxb2 (17... Nxe5 18. Nxe5+ Bxe5 19. O-O+ Ke8 20. Bg6+) 18.
O-O $18 Qxc2 19. Qxc2) 17... Ke7 18. Bb3 hxg5 19. hxg5 c4 20. Bxc4 dxc3 21.
gxf6+ Rxf6 22. Qxg7+ Kd8 23. Kf2 cxb2 24. Rad1 exf4 25. Nd4 fxe3+ 26. Ke2 Qb4
27. Qxf6+ Kc7 28. Nb5+ Qxb5 29. Qd6+ 1-0

