{In this game I analyze the "Miladinovic" plan. White gives his bishop for the
f6 knight and organize an attack against Black's king.} 1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3.
Bg5 c5 4. e3 Be7 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 b6 7. c3 Bb7 8. Bd3 d6 9. Bxf6 $1 {
the Miladinovic plan!} (9. Qe2 Nbd7 10. Bxf6 $6 Nxf6 $1) 9... Bxf6 10. Qe2 a6
11. h4 Nd7 12. a4 $5 {this is interesting but very risky ! (typical Igor
Miladinovic play!) ....White now has a problem with his own king ..as he
cannot castle either way! ........generally his idea is to play Kf1 at some
point, and Rh3-Rg3..but we must now forget that by doing this, his rooks are
unconnected and they lose their potensial! ...and if the center opens with a
well-timed e6-e5, white may have a big problem!} Be7 13. Ne4 h6 (13... Nf6 $1 {
this appears to be simple enough......and if i trade some pieces, then i m
free to play 0-0 as black, and continue with the minority attack} 14. Kf1 Nd5
$1 (14... Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 d5 17. Qd3 O-O 18. Ng5 g6 $132)) 14. Rh3
Qc7 15. Kf1 g6 $2 (15... O-O $132) (15... Nf6 $1) 16. Re1 Qc6 $2 17. c4 Qc7 18.
Kg1 Kf8 19. Rg3 Re8 20. Qd2 Nf6 21. d5 Nh5 (21... e5 22. Nxf6 Bxf6 23. h5) 22.
dxe6 Nxg3 23. exf7 Kxf7 24. fxg3 d5 25. cxd5 Bxd5 26. Rc1 Bc5+ 27. Nxc5 bxc5
28. Bxg6+ Kxg6 29. Qxd5 Qxg3 30. h5+ Kg7 31. Qd7+ Kf6 32. Rf1 Rhf8 33. Nd4+ Kg5
34. Rf5+ 1-0

